[start section id="20112"]

#1 Stage III completely resected colon cancer
This disease was diagnosed in June 2010 and resected by Dr. Adams.  There is no evidence of metastatic disease on CT scans of the abdomen and pelvis as well as on chest imaging.  I had a long discussion with Mrs. Barrett and her husband.  I explained that in this situation, a stage III colon carcinoma, we usually recommend adjuvant chemotherapy to decrease the likelihood of recurrence of cancer.  I explained that even with chemotherapy, the cancer could recur and on the other hand even without chemotherapy, there is a chance that she is cured of the cancer.  I emphasized that because of several risk factors including lymphovascular invasion, stage III disease, and poorly-differentiated histology, I would certainly recommend adjuvant chemotherapy at this point.  Chemotherapy should consist of the FOLFOX combination.  We discussed side-effects of such chemotherapy including nausea, vomiting, immunosuppression, thrombocytopenia, fatigue, peripheral neuropathy, diarrhea, mucositis, and a small chance of coronary vasospasm.  Mrs. Barrett is still eager to go ahead with this therapy.  She would like to have it started here at TSH and then look for an oncologist in Tex.  I have therefore scheduled placement of a Port-a-Cath hopefully for tomorrow and start of chemotherapy with FOLFOX for Monday.  I also explained that follow-up would be required after completion of all therapy.  This should consist of physical examination, a CEA, and other blood work three-months after completion, then a CT-scan after six-months, and a repeat colonoscopy after one-year.  Mrs. Barrett would like to come here for the latter, I have therefore scheduled a colonoscopy,  a return visit with me, as well as a CT-scan and blood work.
#2 Inflammatory bowel disease and primary sclerosing cholangitis
She will follow-up with Dr. Lester later this afternoon for this.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: Yes, not on file at TSH.
PATIENT EDUCATION
Ready to learn, no apparent learning barriers were identified; learning preferences include listening.  Explained diagnosis and treatment plan; patient expressed understanding of the content.

