[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Barrett is a 61-year-old woman who was diagnosed with Crohn's colitis in 1998 and abnormal liver test, consistent with PCS in 2004.  She was followed by yearly colonoscopies for her Crohn's colitis, most recently in September 2009.  Reportedly, no evidence of malignancy was ever found; however, Mrs. Barrett started to feel fatigued especially during the past winter.  Since the fatigue was progressive, she finally sought medical attention again.  In June 2010, she came to SPCMC and was found to be anemic.  A colonoscopy was done on June 25, 2010, the operative report describes mild right and transverse colon inflammatory change, a diminutive rectal polyp, and inflammation of the ileocecal valve.  Random biopsies were taken and the pathology report describes invasive poorly-differentiated adenocarcinoma at the ileocecal valve.  On July 2, 2010, she was taken to the operating room by Dr. Adams for a right hemicolectomy.  The pathology report describes poorly-differentiated grade 4 (of 4) adenocarcinoma forming a 5.2- x 4.1- x 0.9-cm annular circumferential and ulcerated mass in the ascending colon.  The tumor invaded through the muscularis propria and into the pericolic fat.  Lymphatic/vascular invasion was present.  Surgical resection margins were negative; 4 (of 48) regional lymph nodes were involved with adenocarcinoma; therefore, the disease was staged pT3, N2.
Mrs. Barrett now comes to Bergen Regional Medical Center to discuss further therapy.  She states that she has nicely recovered from the surgery, that she has no pain, that she feels back to her normal activity level, that she has good appetite, and has gained 1 pound since the surgery.  She had no medical complaints.

[end section id="20103"]

